#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:4
# 85f7ba3f6f8b47c3806f607219ac9ff5
msgid "Editing E-books"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:6
# edd39aa7324c4db187100f3cb86cadfd
msgid "calibre has an integrated e-book editor that can be used to edit books in the EPUB and AZW3 (Kindle) formats. The editor shows you the HTML and CSS that is used internally inside the book files, with a live preview that updates as you make changes. It also contains various automated tools to perform common cleanup and fixing tasks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:12
# 5a2b438f23ee4bc9886b5e24fbc50416
msgid "You can use this editor by right clicking on any book in calibre and selecting :guilabel:`Edit book`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:0
# bdc6b45d5c2840b88fb59f8b8f4e6727
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:26
# 40111c77986c40fab86c11ed54006f7f
msgid "Basic workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:29
# 4dfaa6160c3f428ead59e11c7b3fb62c
msgid "A video tour of the calibre editor is available `here <http://calibre-ebook.com/demo#tutorials>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:32
# d2b44c8c124747f3936b4b72ea1e3ab1
msgid "When you first open a book with the Edit book tool, you will be presented with a list of files on the left. These are the individual HTML files, stylesheets, images, etc. that make up the content of the book. Simply double click on a file to start editing it. Note that if you want to do anything more sophisticated than making a few small tweaks, you will need to know `HTML Tutorial <http://html.net/tutorials/html/>`_ and `CSS Tutorial <http://html.net/tutorials/css/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:40
# ee190fbaec7e4a669ce76349a6b0df5c
msgid "As you make changes to the HTML or CSS in the editor, the changes will be previewed, live, in the preview panel to the right. When you are happy with how the changes you have made look, click the Save button or use :guilabel:`File->Save` to save your changes into the ebook."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:45
# 623a386482c145c8a9093c051e40425f
msgid "One useful feature is :guilabel:`Checkpoints`. Before you embark on some ambitious set of edits, you can create a checkpoint. The checkpoint will preserve the current state of your book, then if in the future you decide you dont like the changes you have made to you can go back to the state when you created the checkpoint. To create a checkpoint, use :guilabel:`Edit->Create checkpoint`. Checkpoints will also be automatically created for you whenever you run any automated tool like global search and replace. The checkpointing functionality is in addition to the normal Undo/redo mechanism when editing individual files. Checkpoints are useful for when changes are spread over multiple files in the book."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:56
# 9f97077dce974403996a21d39ec70aa1
msgid "That is the basic work flow for editing books -- Open a file, make changes, preview and save. The rest of this manual will discuss the various tools and features present to allow you to perform specific tasks efficiently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:61
# 69742b6d3432410190a49e0365a7bcdf
msgid "The Files Browser"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:67
# 868599a499844f38b1b737e783c62baa
msgid "The :guilabel:`Files Browser` gives you an overview of the various files inside the book you are editing. The files are arranged by category, with text (HTML) files at the top, followed by stylesheet (CSS) files, images and so on. Simply double click on a file to start editing it. Editing is supported for HTML, CSS and image files. The order of text files is the same order that they would be displayed in, if you were reading the book. All other files are arranged alphabetically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:75
# e1ad3180e34845e38a736ba71b92fa2f
msgid "By hovering your mouse over an entry, you can see its size, and also, at the bottom of the screen, the full path to the file inside the book. Note that files inside ebooks are compressed, so the size of the final book is not the sum of the individual file sizes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:80
# caa9966bc5864b4392b71badb5332616
msgid "Many files have special meaning, in the book. These will typically have an icon next to their names, indicating the special meaning. For example, in the picture to the left, you can see that the files :guilabel:`cover_image.jpg` and :guilabel:`titlepage.xhtml` have the icon of a cover next to them, this indicates they are the book cover image and titlepage. Similarly, the :guilabel:`content.opf` file has a metadata icon next to it, indicating the book metadata is present in it and the the :guilabel:`toc.ncx` file has a T icon next to it, indicating it is the Table of Contents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:89
# c5c9ad462e264169bbacb7cf83720260
msgid "You can perform many actions on individual files, by right clicking them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:92
# 094e5abf12e34072af02c97044198255
msgid "Renaming files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:94
# e7794a550f4f4247a77d988c21b81091
msgid "You can rename an individual file by right clicking it and selecting :guilabel:`Rename`. Renaming a file automatically updates all links and references to it throughout the book. So all you have to do is provide the new name, calibre will take care of the rest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:99
# 0611e527876e4e00b81111369b3031b9
msgid "You can also bulk rename many files at once. This is useful if you want the files to have some simple name pattern. For example you might want to rename all the HTML files to have names Chapter-1.html, Chapter-2.html and so on. Select the files you want bulk renamed by holding down the Shift or Ctrl key and clicking the files. Then right click and select :guilabel:`Bulk rename`. Enter a prefix and what number you would like the automatic numbering to start at, click OK and you are done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:108
# f99969b972ca48148acd0dac21d112cb
msgid "Merging files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:110
# 1fef3d0124ec4534a454f3005b5021c9
msgid "Sometimes, you may want to merge two HTML files or two CSS files together. It can sometimes be useful to have everything in a single file. Be wary, though, putting a lot of content into a single file will cause performance problems when viewing the book in a typical ebook reader."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:115
# 9556adada9c4432d989cac08bbf59779
msgid "To merge multiple files together, select them by holding the Ctrl key and clicking on them (make sure you only select files of one type, either all HTML files or all CSS files and so on). Then right click and select merge. That's all, calibre will merge the files, automatically taking care of migrating all links and references to the merged files. Note that merging files can sometimes cause text styling to change, since the individual files could have used different stylesheets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:124
# 4c56cff693de4cff9102964a2eaa1e09
msgid "Changing text file order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:126
# 8594f89cdf2a43d0a1b4f86645a3c7a2
msgid "You can re-arrange the order in which text (HTML) files are opened when reading the book by simply dragging and dropping them in the Files browser. For the technically inclined, this is called re-ordering the book spine. Note that you have to drop the items *between* other items, not on top of them, this can be a little fiddly until you get used to it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:133
# 9ca48ba1f78b4fd787a981538d07989a
msgid "Marking the cover"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:135
# a2dd7c4d137d45b9ac0ef6a267e39698
msgid "E-books typically have a cover image. This image is indicated in the Files Browser by the icon of a brown book next to the image name. If you want to designate some other image as the cover, you can do so by right clicking on the file and choosing :guilabel:`Mark as cover`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:140
# 0d095cd4b08d422ab60fe73bbad18e84
msgid "In addition, EPUB files has the concept of a *titlepage*. A title page is a HTML file that acts as the title page/cover for the book. You can mark an HTML file as the titlepage when editing EPUBs by right-clicking. Be careful that the file you mark contains only the cover information. If it contains other content, such as the first chapter, then that content will be lost if the user ever converts the EPUB file in calibre to another format. This is because when converting, calibre assumes that the marked title page contains only the cover and no other content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:150
# ff2b70466e7a45158bdd9c1617e09c84
msgid "Deleting files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:152
# 4e0c34ca41de4db9bd038f33889166b8
msgid "You can delete files by either right clicking on them or by selecting them and pressing the Delete key. Deleting a file removes all references to the file from the OPF file, saving you that chore. However, references in other places are not removed, you can use the Check Book tool to easily find and remove/replace them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:159
# 9bf2a0fd21ae4e37b460cf01f3e31992
msgid "Export of files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:161
# cbbfaaa7adae42aebe5e0489d5ff1e50
msgid "You can export a file from inside the book to somewhere else on your computer. This is useful if you want to work on the file in isolation, with specialised tools. To do this, simply right click on the file and choose :guilabel:`Export`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:166
# 79d894e9a29a4085bafc2db214028073
msgid "Once you are done working on the exported file, you can re-import it into the book, by right clicking on the file again and choosing :guilabel:`Replace with file...` which will allow you to replace the file in the book with the previously exported file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:172
# 92312dc91f3e4a8291ad4a55974c3355
msgid "Adding new images/fonts/etc. or creating new blank files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:174
# 4b85d309bd5247a5810f2012c6433c32
msgid "You can add a new image, font, stylesheet, etc. from your computer into the book by clicking :guilabel:`File->New file`. This lets you either import a file by clicking the :guilabel:`Import resource file` button or create a new blank html file or stylesheet by simply entering the file name into the box for the new file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:179
# c93ec3a8226648b0a92da800369e12a6
msgid "You can also import multiple files into the book at once using File->Import files into book."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:183
# 4cd359213d9e4e31b06c058c0bf3c36f
msgid "Replacing files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:185
# 9925ac3b84a84542aea78397c5e9f284
msgid "You can easily replace existing files in the book, by right clicking on the file and choosing replace. This will automatically update all links and references, in case the replacement file has a different name than the file being replaced."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:191
# c16bf2a019174b53906860b6c804ac38
msgid "Linking stylesheets to HTML files efficiently"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:193
# f962982104c54fd9ba6d968ac36356f4
msgid "As a convenience, you can select multiple HTML files in the Files Browser, right click and choose Link stylesheets to have calibre automatically insert the <link> tags for those stylesheets into all the selected HTML files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:203
# fd770c2e624a44218a0bb0bb009a1e34
msgid "Search & Replace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:205
# ff15b4f7bdf44a71b899a9e8238400d1
msgid "Edit Book has a very powerful search and replace interface that allows you to search and replace text in the current file, across all files and even in a marked region of the current file. You can search using a normal search or using regular expressions. To learn how to use regular expressions for advanced searching, see :ref:`regexptutorial`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:215
# 698f1fdc09d44188bfe642d06a11a8a9
msgid "Start the search and replace via the :guilabel:`Search->Find/replace` menu entry (you must be editing an HTML or CSS file)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:218
# fa731b66960e45b6b18dbd846976d8ba
msgid "Type the text you want to find into the Find box and its replacement into the Replace box. You can the click the appropriate buttons to Find the next match, replace the current match and replace all matches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:222
# 6b243550c64c49ecac79e145dcef1d74
msgid "Using the drop downs at the bottom of the box, you can have the search operate over the current file, all text files, all style files or all files. You can also choose the search mode to be a normal (string) search or a regular expression search."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:227
# 978ee2ea07464153af256809f0849835
msgid "You can count all the matches for a search expression via :guilabel:`Search->Count all`. The count will run over whatever files/regions you have selected in the dropdown box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:231
# aba81972320a4a73b7cb41c0602c1126
msgid "You can also go to a specific line in the currently open editor via :guilabel:`Search->Go to line`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:235
# 26010c7416144737893b08c828c29fe0
msgid "Remember, to harness the full power of search and replace, you will need to use regular expressions. See :ref:`regexptutorial`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:239
# e7e965e2baae4becadecc57541a36242
msgid "Saved searches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:241
# e0ee4d434d70426b996750fa151d0217
msgid "You can save frequently used search/replace expressions and reuse them multiple times. To save a search simply right click in the Find box and select :guilabel:`Save current search`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:244
# 6f28e21d454e48248ba02dadc1563b88
msgid "You can bring up the dialog of saved searches via :guilabel:`Search->Saved Searches`. This will present you with a list of search and replace expressions that you can apply. You can even select multiple entries in the list by holding down the Ctrl Key while clicking so as to run multiple search and replace expressions in a single operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:251
# 5906c12c383a45f8a15ab0abe7d88a4b
msgid "Function mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:253
# 2501c35e4b1446bea14e07b3c9659cd1
msgid "Function mode allows you to write arbitrarily powerful python functions that are run on every Find/replace. You can do pretty much any text manipulation you like in function mode. For more information, see :doc:`function_mode`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:258
# f8cd21f4bdbc49d5abb4d076ff4ad8ce
msgid "Automated tools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:260
# bb9c17fed5cc4ba593e70138856a3d9d
msgid "Edit book has various tools to help with common tasks. These are accessed via the :guilabel:`Tools` menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:264
# ba4d6f265374474f80b3d9943be6a449
msgid "Edit the Table of Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:266
# cf4f5f0090d343868ba54ec374255850
msgid "There is a dedicated tool to ease editing of the Table of Contents. Launch it with :guilabel:`Tools->Table of Contents->Edit Table of Contents`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:273
# b32f7965b8954984ae469b61e3731b36
msgid "The Edit Table of Contents tool shows you the current Table of Contents (if any) on the left. Simply double click on any entry to change its text. You can also re-arrange entries by drag and drop or by using the buttons to the right."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:277
# 03c5463976ae45e8a724e84ecc20198f
msgid "For books that do not have a pre-existing Table of Contents, the tool gives you various options to auto-generate a Table of Contents from the text. You can generate from the headings in the document, from links, from individual files and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:282
# 0c0efb5402374aaa8ed4314bb3114ae6
msgid "You can edit individual entries by clicking on them and then clicking the :guilabel:`Change the location this entry points to` button. This will open up a mini-preview of the book, simply move the mouse cursor over the book view panel, and click where you want the entry to point to. A thick green line will show you the location. Click OK once you are happy with the location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:293
# 52e8a85b99174f6fbe9873d8b973950d
msgid "Check Book"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:295
# 64cb151868d54c7c9350c70ec27dd0a6
msgid "The :guilabel:`Check Book` tool searches your book for problems that could prevent it working as intended on actual reader devices. Activate it via :guilabel:`Tools->Check Book`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:303
# 8ff25bfcc5f348438e111ea767efbeec
msgid "Any problems found are reported in a nice, easy to use list. Clicking any entry in the list shows you some help about that error as well as giving you the option to auto-fix that error, if the error can be fixed automatically. You can also double click the error to open the location of the error in an editor, so you can fix it yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:310
# c7578e8299b74c5c96175be56bc42f35
msgid "Some of the checks performed are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:312
# 18dae0c03c894283b3a435afbb75c7ff
msgid "Malformed HTML markup. Any HTML markup that does not parse as well-formed XML is reported. Correcting it will ensure that your markup works as intended in all contexts. calibre can also auto-fix these errors, but auto-fixing can sometimes have unexpected effects, so use with care. As always, a checkpoint is created before auto-fixing so you can easily revert all changes. Auto-fixing works by parsing the markup using the HTML5 algorithm, which is highly fault tolerant and then converting to well formed XML."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:321
# 9a3e91ab97a842679da999942fe9962d
msgid "Malformed or unknown CSS styles. Any CSS that is not valid or that has properties not defined in the CSS 2.1 standard (plus a few from CSS 3) are reported. CSS is checked in all stylesheets, inline style attributes and <style> tags in HTML files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:326
# 949448f98b504fafa809b8d7ee67949c
msgid "Broken links. Links that point to files inside the book that are missing are reported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:329
# 4586b6bccb6c4835939b917f171bf280
msgid "Unreferenced files. Files in the book that are not referenced by any other file or are not in the spine are reported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:332
# 5924e60f24984421afa86b5b396db91c
msgid "Various common problems in OPF files such as duplicate spine or manifest items, broken idrefs or meta cover tags, missing required sections and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:336
# ccef94ce0fc34900851971c3fe54435a
msgid "Various compatibility checks for known problems that can cause the book to malfunction on reader devices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:340
# f18b319a53b64acca5dc3989e4e70ad7
msgid "Add a cover"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:342
# 345743649ca942edac6f98727de83efa
msgid "You can easily add a cover to the book via :guilabel:`Tools->Add cover`. This allows you to either choose an existing image in the book as the cover or import a new image into the book and make it the cover. When editing EPUB files, the HTML wrapper for the cover is automatically generated. If an existing cover in the book is found, it is replaced. The tool also automatically takes care of correctly marking the cover files as covers in the OPF."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:351
# 12630d8de7ce4fbcbf77ca562feb376a
msgid "Embedding referenced fonts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:353
# 740cdaa049ef4de093de7a98c2493583
msgid "Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Embed reference fonts`, this tool finds all fonts referenced in the book and if they are not already embedded, searches your computer for them and embeds them into the book, if found. Please make sure that you have the necessary copyrights for embedding commercially licensed fonts, before doing this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:360
# 8f1d1f5be4f7485dbb97427f20963bb0
msgid "Subsetting embedded fonts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:362
# 5e7916dc75544af6ba47fcf4546951fc
msgid "Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Subset embedded fonts`, this tool reduces all the fonts in the book to only contain glyphs for the text actually present in the book. This commonly reduces the size of the font files by ~ 50%. However, be aware that once the fonts are subset, if you add new text whose characters are not previously present in the subset font, the font will not work for the new text. So do this only as the last step in your workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:370
# deabd25c9fc649708f3ed5aed60c4a1b
msgid "Smartening punctuation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:372
# fd13c0007fac436f92e5999b04ffefc6
msgid "Convert plain text dashes, ellipsis, quotes, multiple hyphens, etc. into their typographically correct equivalents. Note that the algorithm can sometimes generate incorrect results, especially when single quotes at the start of contractions are involved. Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Smarten punctuation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:379
# cf20067dba124581ae2bdcf56f738af3
msgid "Removing unused CSS rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:381
# 07b5d5c022874daa95cd7ce2d85939cc
msgid "Remove all unused CSS rules from stylesheets and <style> tags. Some books created from production templates can have a large number of extra CSS rules that dont match any actual content. These extra rules can slow down readers that need to process them all. Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Remove unused CSS`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:388
# 6f4aa6943a5c460eaf9c7d3c6bbd9080
msgid "Fix HTML"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:390
# 9334051c672243cc9e9c2fa5340d0fb0
msgid "This tool simply converts HTML that cannot be parsed as XML into well-formed XML. It is very common in ebooks to have non-well-formed XML, so this tool simply automates the process of fixing such HTML. The tool works by parsing the HTML using the HTML5 algorithm (the algorithm used in all modern browsers) and then converting the result into XML. Be aware that auto-fixing can sometimes have counter-intuitive results. If you prefer, you can use the Check Book tool discussed above to find and manually correct problems in the HTML. Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Fix HTML`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:400
# e2c906d1fc2449d3a67eceeeccc548d1
msgid "Beautifying files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:402
# 00e631dace7247f3b508fbf8401be398
msgid "This tool is used to auto-format all HTML and CSS files so that they \"look pretty\". The code is auto-indented so that it lines up nicely, blank lines are inserted where appropriate and so on. Note that beautifying also auto-fixes broken HTML/CSS. Therefore, if you dont want any auto-fixing to be performed, first use the Check Book tool to correct all problems and only then run beautify.  Accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Beautify all files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:410
# 96eaf306046143eab28b8da0dfb5f0d1
msgid "In HTML any text can have significant whitespace, via the CSS white-space directive. Therefore, beautification could potentially change the rendering of the HTML. To avoid this as far as possible, the beautify algorithm only beautifies block level tags that contain other block level tags. So, for example, text inside a <p> tag will not have its whitespace changed. But a <body> tag that contains only other <p> and <div> tags will be beautified.  This can sometimes mean that a particular file will not be affected by beautify as it has no suitable block level tags. In such cases you can try different beautification tools, that are less careful, for example: `HTML Tidy <http://infohound.net/tidy/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:423
# cd8ac2c966c24d658a9491cf0ac1d6e3
msgid "Insert inline Table of Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:425
# 84f3d84bf45b4977b4680efed52a1f3c
msgid "Normally in ebooks, the Table of Contents is separate from the main text and is typically accessed via a special Table of Contents button/menu in the ebook reading device. You can also have calibre automatically generate an *inline* Table of Contents that becomes part of the text of the book. It is generated based on the currently defined Table of Contents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:431
# 67589a81dcfa459db04b46f0a9643e12
msgid "If you use this tool multiple times, each invocation will cause the previously created inline Table of Contents to be replaced. The tool can be accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Table of Contents->Insert inline Table of Contents`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:436
# d34b529c174d447fbd6a546c4a412208
msgid "Set Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:438
# 4bc59916d665489e9df4a8a3107c0636
msgid "This tool is used to set *semantics* in EPUB files. Semantics are simply, links in the OPF file that identify certain locations in the book as having special meaning. You can use them to identify the foreword, dedication, cover, table of contents, etc. Simply choose the type of semantic information you want to specify and then select the location in the book the link should point to. This tool can be accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Set semantics`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:446
# 9fdff410865c4cdba24af00296ad297c
msgid "Filter style information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:448
# 3547990a5d0346c98c6a0ec53d4982b5
msgid "This tool can be used to easily remove specified CSS style properties from the entire book. You can tell it what properties you want removed, for example, ``color, background-color, line-height`` and it will remove them from everywhere they occur --- stylesheets, ``<style>`` tags and inline ``style`` attributes. After removing the style information, a summary of all the changes made is displayed so you can see exactly what was changed. The tool can be accessed via :guilabel:`Tools->Filter style information`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:459
# 8147099d9e2d4bc68e5c668e7f4671cf
msgid "Checkpoints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:461
# 093308ed375f47c18bf75516c37aa905
msgid ":guilabel:`Checkpoints` are a way to mark the current state of the book as \"special\". You can then go on to do whatever changes you want to the book and if you dont like the results, return to the checkpointed state. Checkpoints are automatically created every time you run any of the automated tools described in the previous section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:467
# 2c15eb39dbc544fe8bba4f1f4d60f925
msgid "You can create a checkpoint via :guilabel:`Edit->Create checkpoint`. And go back to a previous checkpoint with :guilabel:`Edit->Revert to ...`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:470
# b4aed73342f548c8a378b8027251b7e9
msgid "The checkpointing functionality is in addition to the normal Undo/redo mechanism when editing individual files. Checkpoints are particularly useful for when changes are spread over multiple files in the book or when you wish to be able to revert a large group of related changes as a whole."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:475
# 9df940e5ecee4dadad19c6dc1f3ebc3e
msgid "You can see a list of available checkpoints via :guilabel:`View->Checkpoints`. You can compare the current state of the book to a specified checkpoint using the :ref:`diff` tool -- by selecting the checkpoint of interest and clicking the :guilabel:`Compare` button. The :guilabel:`Revert to` button restores the book to the selected checkpoint, undoing all changes since that checkpoint was created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:483
# b74c9a302a5740719c5fc48419d16077
msgid "The Live Preview panel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:489
# 428798b09a4046fcacfc2c25016414f3
msgid "The :guilabel:`File Preview` gives you an overview of the various files inside The live preview panel shows you the changes you are making live (with a second or two of delay). As you edit HTML or CSS files, the preview panel is updated automatically to reflect your changes. As you move the cursor around in the editor, the preview panel will track its location, showing you the corresponding location in the book. Clicking in the preview panel, will cause the cursor in the editor to be positioned over the element you clicked. If you click a link pointing to another file in the book, that file will be opened in the edit and the preview panel, automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:499
# 9b5ced1311794b07bd60c9c43c6f5f34
msgid "You can turn off the automatic syncing of position and live preview of changes -- by buttons under the preview panel. The live update of the preview panel only happens when you are not actively typing in the editor, so as not to be distracting or slow you down, waiting for the preview to render."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:504
# ca74c1880a194da89b4562b65b46e13e
msgid "The preview panel shows you how the text will look when viewed. However, the preview panel is not a substitute for actually testing your book an actual reader device. It is both more, and less capable than an actual reader. It will tolerate errors and sloppy markup much better than most reader devices. It will also not show you page margins, page breaks and embedded fonts that use font name aliasing. Use the preview panel while you are working on the book, but once you are done, review it in an actual reader device or software emulator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:513
# 59cb11a441de4dfd97925f8651df233c
msgid "The preview panel does not support embedded fonts if the name of the font inside the font file does not match the name in the CSS @font-face rule. You can use the Check Book tool to quickly find and fix any such problem fonts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:519
# cb377b50fafd43af966b290332512bd9
msgid "Splitting HTML files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:523
# d712dd4a130d46feb2c28291c25e3477
msgid "One, perhaps non-obvious, use of the preview panel is to split long HTML files. While viewing the file you want to split, click the :guilabel:`split mode` button under the preview panel |spmb|. Then simply move your mouse to the place where you want to split the file and click. A thick green line will show you exactly where the split will happen as you move your mouse. Once you have found the location you want, simply click and the split will be performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:530
# 0ee88598c5ce4ffc8d9c4c2828fd527e
msgid "Splitting the file will automatically update all links and references that pointed into the bottom half of the file and will open the newly split file in an editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:534
# bd577aa8404d412b94cee7a89f5826f7
msgid "You can also split a single HTML file at multiple locations automatically, by right clicking inside the file in the editor and choosing :guilabel:`Split at multiple locations`. This will allow you to easily split a large file at all heading tags or all tags having a certain class and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:544
# b2e17e203609434dac562315ce3c0cb0
msgid "The Live CSS panel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:551
# c7853d747f244a41b1c5274e7de28889
msgid "The :guilabel:`Live CSS` panel shows you all the style rules that apply to the tag you are currently editing. The name of tag, along with its line number in the editor are displayed, followed by a list of matching style rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:555
# 76ccdfd4fb3c4c35b473a3c50ed09547
msgid "It is a great way to quickly see which style rules apply to any tag. The view also has clickable links (in blue), which take you directly to the location where the style was defined, in case you wish to make any changes to the style rules. Style rules that apply directly to the tag, as well as rules that are inherited from parent tags are shown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:561
# 9fe38c11e0314885b8c21ece8d475756
msgid "The panel also shows you what the finally calculated styles for the tag are. Properties in the list that are superseded by higher priority rules are shown with a line through them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/edit.rst:565
# cf20e42fbd634996a1c887d29dbcb99d
msgid "You can enable the Live CSS panel via :guilabel:`View->Live CSS`."
msgstr ""

